requirement description

paper

Draw a picture of Manhattan from the paper, the text labels look better.

https://www.nature.com/articles/s41588-018-0045-8

fromhttps://www.nature.com/articles/s41588-018-0045-8

application scenario

SNP

Show the distribution of SNP on each chromosome, usually presented as the first figure in an exon sequencing article.

Input file

easy_input.csvSNPpvaluetypegene

typegenegeneSNPtype

easy_input.csv, including chromosome name, SNP number, position on the chromosome (which base), pvalue, type, gene name.

Type and gene are not required, if the gene name can be provided, it should be written in the gene column; if different shapes are used to display different classes of SNPs, the type will be written in type.

library(dplyr)

gwas <- read.csv("easy_input.csv", as.is = T)

SNP

If you dont provide the chromosome length yourself, use the SNP position maximum as the chromosome length and run the following paragraph

chrx <- gwas %>% 
  group_by(chr) %>% 
  summarise(chr_len=max(POS)) %>% 
  
  #x
  #calculate the starting position of each chromosome on the x-axis
  mutate(chrx=cumsum(chr_len)-chr_len) %>%
  select(-chr_len) %>% # delete chromosome length
  data.frame()

Karyotype.txt

Karyotype.txt, if you provide your own chromosome length file, run the following paragraph

chrom <- read.table("Karyotype.txt", header = T, as.is = T)
head(chrom)
##   chr   chr_len
## 1   1 305554054
## 2   2 163324765
## 3   3 156204919
## 4   4 154452577
## 5   5 113518423
## 6   6 181673133
#x
#calculate the starting position of each chromosome on the x-axis
chrom$chrx <- c(0,cumsum(as.numeric(chrom$chr_len))[-nrow(chrom)])
chrx <- data.frame(chr = chrom$chr, chrx = chrom$chrx)
chrx$chr <- factor(chrx$chr,levels=c(1:18,"X","Y"))# order chromosomes

SNP

calculate the coordinates of each SNP

#x
#calculate the coordinates of each chromosome on the x-axis
gwas <- left_join(gwas, chrx, by=c("chr"="chr")) %>%
  #arrange(chr, POS) %>%
  mutate(SNPx=POS+chrx)

#-log10(P-value)y
#take -log10(P-value) as the y-axis coordinate
gwas$SNPy <- -log10(gwas$P_value)

classify by threshold

#
#set threshold
logPcutoff <- 4

#
#whether or not the threshold is exceeded is divided into two categories, which will be distinguished later by dots of different sizes
gwas$pcut <- rep("0", nrow(gwas))
gwas[gwas$SNPy > logPcutoff,]$pcut <- "1"

#SNP
#write text labels only for SNP above a certain threshold
gwas$label <- rep(NA, nrow(gwas))
gwas[gwas$SNPy > logPcutoff,]$label <- paste(gwas[gwas$SNPy > 4,]$gene,gwas[gwas$SNPy > 4,]$SNP,sep = "\n")
#
#if the gene name is not provided, use the following line
#gwas[gwas$SNPy > logPcutoff,]$label <- gwas[gwas$SNPy > 4,]$SNP

Start drawing

Draw dots first

#
#don't like the default color scheme, customize enough colors
mycol <- rep(c("#223D6C","#D20A13","#FFD121","#088247","#11AA4D","#58CDD9","#7A142C","#5D90BA","#431A3D","#91612D","#6E568C","#E0367A","#D8D155","#64495D","#7CC767"),2)

#x
#chromosome names as x-axis labels
axisdf = gwas %>% group_by(chr) %>% summarize(center=( max(SNPx) + min(SNPx) ) / 2 )

library("ggplot2")
p <- ggplot(data = gwas, mapping = aes(x = SNPx, y = SNPy)) + 
  geom_point(aes(colour = chr, # use a different color for each chromosome
                 shape = type, # different shapes for different types
                 size = pcut)) + # dots above and below the threshold use different sizes
  #
  #if there are no categories, or if you don't need to display the categories in a different shape, run the following line
  #geom_point(aes(colour = CHR)) +
  scale_size_discrete(range = c(0.5,2)) + # range of dot sizes
  #scale_shape_manual(values = c(20,8,15)) + # shape of the dot
  
  #
  #add a red line with threshold
  geom_hline(yintercept = logPcutoff, color = 'red') +
  
  xlab("") + ylab(expression(-log[10](P))) + 
  scale_x_continuous(label = axisdf$chr, breaks= axisdf$center,
                     expand = expand_scale(mult = c(0,0.02))) + # left to the end, leave the right blank
  scale_y_continuous(expand = expand_scale(mult = c(0,0.04))) + # bottom to the end, leave the top blank
  
  theme_bw() + # remove background color
  theme(panel.grid =element_blank()) + # remove gridlines
  theme(panel.border = element_blank()) + # remove outer border
  theme(axis.text = element_text(size = rel(0.8)), # axis label font size
        axis.line = element_line(colour = "black")) # display lines along the axes
## Warning: Using size for a discrete variable is not advised.
## Warning: `expand_scale()` was deprecated in ggplot2 3.3.0.
##  Please use `expansion()` instead.
## This warning is displayed once every 8 hours.
## Call `lifecycle::last_lifecycle_warnings()` to see where this warning was
## generated.
p1 <- p + scale_color_manual(values = mycol) + # use custom colors
  guides(colour = FALSE, size = FALSE) + # chromosome legend not shown
  theme(legend.background = element_blank(), 
        legend.title = element_blank(),
        legend.text = element_text(size = 8), # legend font size
        legend.position = c(1,1),legend.justification = c(1,1)) # the legend for the shape is placed in the upper right corner
## Warning: The `<scale>` argument of `guides()` cannot be `FALSE`. Use "none" instead as
## of ggplot2 3.3.4.
## This warning is displayed once every 8 hours.
## Call `lifecycle::last_lifecycle_warnings()` to see where this warning was
## generated.
## Warning: A numeric `legend.position` argument in `theme()` was deprecated in ggplot2
## 3.5.0.
##  Please use the `legend.position.inside` argument of `theme()` instead.
## This warning is displayed once every 8 hours.
## Call `lifecycle::last_lifecycle_warnings()` to see where this warning was
## generated.
p1

#
#the legend is placed at the bottom
p2 <- p + theme(axis.ticks.x = element_blank(), axis.text.x = element_blank()) +#x remove x-axis scale and labels
  guides(color = guide_legend(nrow = 2), # the legend for the chromosomes is in two rows
         size = FALSE) + # the legend does not show the point size
  theme(legend.background = element_blank(), 
        legend.title = element_blank(),
        legend.box = "vertical", # two legends are placed vertically
        legend.margin=margin(t= 0, unit='cm'), # the legend does not leave a margin
        legend.spacing = unit(0,"in"), # two legends are next to each other
        legend.position = "bottom") + # the legend is placed at the bottom
  scale_color_manual(labels = paste0("Chr",unique(gwas$chr)),
                     values = mycol)
p2

Add more arrows and labels

library(ggrepel)
p2 + geom_text_repel(aes(label = label), 
                     size = 2, # font size of label text
                     point.padding = unit(0.5, "lines"), # labelpoint connection display between label and point
                     segment.colour = "black", #  color of connection (line + arrow)
                     segment.size = 0.4, #  thickness of connection (line + arrow)
                     arrow = arrow(angle = 20, length = unit(0.04,"inches")), # ?arrow arrow setting reference ?arrow
                     ylim = c(logPcutoff, max(gwas$SNPy)), # label limit the drawing area of the label
                     direction = "both", # xylabel adjust the position of the label in the x and y directions by default
                     min.segment.length = 0, #0.5 arrows with a default length of less than 0.5 are not drawn
                     na.rm = TRUE #NA no prompt to remove NA
                     )

#pdf
#save to PDF file
ggsave("Manhattan.pdf",width = 7,height = 4)

You can also add borders to the labels

p1 + geom_label_repel(aes(label = label),
                    size = 2,
                    point.padding = unit(0.5, "lines"), 
                    
                    label.size = 0.1, # label the width of the border outside the label
                    label.r = unit(0.2, "lines"), # label the right-angled arc of the frame outside the label
                    
                    segment.colour = "black", 
                    segment.size = 0.5, 
                    arrow = arrow(length = unit(0.1,"cm")), 
                    ylim = c(logPcutoff, max(gwas$SNPy)), 
                    direction = "both", 
                    min.segment.length = 0,
                    na.rm = TRUE 
)
